        <tr>
          <td class="post-content">
            <div class="post-content-inner">
              
              A little background:<br />I started at my current job 6 months ago, as a Systems Administrator. We're a small IT department; 3 'admin' staff including the IT Manager, a Solutions Architect, a bunch of developers and the Head of IT who runs the whole department and is also relatively new to the company.<br />In the last year or so we were bought out by a large US corporation and are currently totally hamstrung with what we can afford to do - i.e. nothing, as we're forced to stretch our budget cycle out to 18 months and wait for the US to begin their new fiscal year.<br /><br />Given that the company has always underfunded IT (Despite it being, basically, a data-driven company) this is stretching us. There's a freeze on headcount, or expenditure of pretty much any kind, unless it's very small beans or absolutely vital.<br /><br />I am - so far - loving the job. I'm getting to do far more than I ever did in previous roles, and have already achieved a huge amount in the time that I've been there, for very little outlay. I have big plans, once we get some cash.<br /><br /><br /><br />I joined the company during a reshuffle. One of the role changes was a developer moving off to concentrate on DBA duty for a non-IT team that does a lot of data manipulation. He also happened to be the 'Security Officer' (read: Information Security Manager with very little to no actual power) for the company, which is ISO 27001 certified.<br /><br />I joined with a CV mostly built in .gov and .mod establishments and, as such, was the most 'Security' knowledgeable guy they had on board. To back this up, I'll note that most of our file shares currently have 'Everyone' set to 'Full Control' and I've had to redesign the AD from the ground up to include Capability Management and Role grouping, etc.<br />(Rather than try and persevere with a spaghetti of the existing file system, I'm just going to design an entirely new one when we get more storage).<br /><br />I was asked to add the 'Security Officer' hat to my role. I had a sit-down with the developer who was doing it, had a brief 15 minute chat and that was that. I figured, in the immortal words of Top Gear, 'How hard can it be?'<br /><br /><br /><br />Last week, we had an ISO27001 Surveillance Audit. I spent the whole day in a room with one of the auditors, and I think I would have liked it more if he'd <span style="font-style: italic">actually</span> bent me over the table and inserted a series of large objects into me. That's what it felt like, but I'd at least not have walked away feeling totally fucking useless.<br /><br /><br />The upshot was that, whilst our ISMS covered most of the bases, it was clear that as a company we were woefully underprepared. The previous 'Head of IT' had gotten the company certified by hook or by crook, without real thought being applied to a lot of things that were produced for it.<br /><br />The auditors expected that I was the 'Information Security Manager' and thus gave me a proper drubbing for not being up to snuff (though they did say afterwards that, considering I'd been in the role 5 months, it was quite impressive). I pointed out halfway through the day that this was not my main role, outlined what that main role was, and the general impression was 'Um, you can't do this part time'.<br /><br /><br />In order to do justice to the role, I reckon I would need to give up about 50% of my time - at least in the first year - to getting everything shipshape. The auditors panned me for not knowing legal procedures and precedents where they were required. They insisted I know far more about employment law and procedures than I did (i.e. nothing - I assumed that's what HR was for), and so forth.<br /><br />I'm an IT guy. I got into IT for specific reasons, and I took this job because I believed I was going in to contribute a huge amount to their IT setup, and get a whole lot out in return.<br /><br />The money is <span style="font-weight: bold">not</span> good. In fact, it's the lowest paid IT job I've ever had by some margin.<br /><br />The business now appears to anticipate that I will add to my already-overstacked workload and assume a role that I have no meaningful experience for, no real desire to perform, for at least 10k per annum less than someone would be paid if they were doing it as a full-time job.<br /><br /><br />So, I'm planning a sit down with my two managers.<br />I intend to outline the work that will be required to get us fully up to scratch (we have a full re-certification in November). I intend to assert that this goes far beyond how the role was originally sold to me, as well as my displeasure at facing the possibility of having to sacrifice up to 50% of my time doing actual productive things that I enjoy and that are making a real difference to the way the company's IT is working.<br /><br />In all honesty, if push came to shove and they said 'This is now your role and you have to do this', I would be looking for another job straight away. Naturally, that's not the angle I want to play this with.<br /><br />Does this seem fair enough?<br />I'm certainly not wanting to come across as an employee who says &quot;I only want to do stuff I like&quot;, because I'm more than happy to take on any required role - as long as it is within the scope (roughly) of the job I signed up for.<br />It's become abundantly clear that the ISM role is much wider than that, and it's a role I do not wish to perform.

              

              
              
            </div>
          </td>
        </tr>
        
