          <td class="post-content">
            <div class="post-content-inner">
              
              It's an interesting dynamic at the moment.<br />Old management are out, new management are in, in certain areas. There's appetite for change in some places, unwillingness in others, but no money to actually do anything.<br /><br />That should change come June, and the woeful lack of underinvestment will be addressed with our 'wish list':<br />- New servers<br />- More SAN<br />- Tools for the job (System Center, Varonis, etc)<br />- Training<br />- Etcetera.<br /><br />From an IT point of view, it's currently a sucky time but is getting better.<br /><br />I was discussing with a colleague today, who admitted to me that I've achieved a huge amount in the 6 months thus far, and have great ideas for the future. He also admitted that, if I were to give up my time for something else in a significant capacity, those things would never get done because nobody else has the capacity for it.<br />We're a three-man team - myself, the aforementioned colleague and my immediate boss who has been requested to move away from Sys Admin duties and into actually 'management' duties.<br />Both have been in the place a long time and their skills are significantly outdated.<br /><br />I think I'll have to sell that quite hard.<br /><br />Re: getting re-certified, I certainly believe that our Head of Department and the president of the company itself would like things to be ironclad. Things before were certainly done with an 'it'll do' attitude, which is how we are where we are now.<br /><br />I could certainly easily get us through that way. The other way would take a lot of time and effort, which I'd rather be putting towards actually getting our shockingly outdated, outmoded systems up to snuff.

              

              
              
            </div>
